            <h2>Heritage Sites of India</h2>
            <div class="heritage-container">
                <div class="heritage-item">
                    <img src="/images/taj-mahal-heritage.png" alt="Taj Mahal" class="heritage-image">
                    <h3>Taj Mahal</h3>
                    <p>The Taj Mahal in Agra is a UNESCO World Heritage Site and a symbol of eternal love. Built by Mughal Emperor Shah Jahan in memory of his wife Mumtaz Mahal, it features stunning white marble architecture blending Persian, Islamic, and Indian styles. The Taj Mahalâ€™s intricate carvings and inlaid gemstones, along with its changing colors throughout the day, create a breathtaking visual. The symmetrical design symbolizes both paradise and the afterlife, with gardens and water features adding to its beauty. It remains one of the world's most famous landmarks and a cultural symbol of India.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="heritage-item">
                    <img src="/images/hampi.jpg" alt="Hampi" class="heritage-image">
                    <h3>Hampi</h3>
                    <p>Hampi, a UNESCO World Heritage Site in Karnataka, was once the capital of the Vijayanagara Empire. Known for its stunning temples and ruins, Hampi offers a glimpse into the grandeur of this ancient city. The Virupaksha and Vittala temples, along with the Stone Chariot, are notable highlights. Hampi's dramatic landscape of boulder-strewn hills and lush greenery adds to its allure. Today, it remains a popular destination for history lovers and spiritual seekers.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="heritage-item">
                    <img src="/images/jaipur.jpg" alt="Jaipur" class="heritage-image">
                    <h3>Jaipur</h3>
                    <p>Jaipur, also known as the Pink City, is famous for its historic forts and palaces, including the Amber Fort and City Palace. As a UNESCO World Heritage Site, it showcases the vibrant culture and royal heritage of Rajasthan. The city's pink-hued architecture and bustling markets make it a lively and unique destination.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="heritage-item">
                    <img src="/images/Khajuraho.jpg" alt="Khajuraho" class="heritage-image">
                    <h3>Khajuraho Temples</h3>
                    <p>The Khajuraho Temples in Madhya Pradesh, a UNESCO World Heritage Site, are renowned for their intricate carvings. Built between 950 and 1050 AD, they feature stunning sculptures depicting daily life, religious scenes, and erotic art. The temples' unique architecture and detailed artwork offer a window into the cultural and religious life of ancient India. The Kandariya Mahadev Temple and Lakshmana Temple are among the highlights.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="heritage-item">
                    <img src="/images/qutubminar.jpg" alt="Qutub Minar" class="heritage-image">
                    <h3>Qutub Minar</h3>
                    <p>The Qutub Minar in Delhi is the tallest brick minaret in the world, built in the 12th century. A UNESCO World Heritage Site, it showcases Indo-Islamic architecture with intricate carvings and inscriptions. The surrounding Qutub complex includes several historic structures, making it a significant site for history enthusiasts.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>
    </div>
    
